article.description:
Tina Thompson scored nine of her 22 points in
the fourth quarter Friday night to help the Houston Comets pull
away for a 72-58 victory over the New York Liberty.
article.headline: Thompson helps Comets keep struggling Liberty at bay
article.linkText: Thompson helps Comets keep struggling Liberty at bay
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Although the New York Liberty got off to a
better start than in the teams' last meeting a week ago, the
Houston Comets still pulled away for another easy win.

Tina Thompson scored nine of her 22 points in the fourth quarter
and Houston beat New York 72-58 Friday night.

The Liberty, who trailed 7-0 and allowed a franchise-record 97
points in a 35-point loss at Houston last Friday, led late in the
first half of this game.

"They were hot, they couldn't miss a shot and it wasn't that
they weren't contested," Thompson said. "They really made some
really tough plays in the first half."

Dominique Canty had 16 points and Michelle Snow added 15 points
and seven rebounds to help the Comets (8-3) beat the Liberty for
the second time in eight days and win their fourth of six overall.
Houston increased its lead in the Western Conference to one game
over Los Angeles.

Sheryl Swoopes had six points and became the third player in
WNBA history to top 4,000 in her career. She trails only Los
Angeles' Lisa Leslie (4,928) and teammate Thompson (4,054).

"We played well, got a lot of firepower," said the Comets'
Dawn Staley, selected to the WNBA All-Decade team earlier this week
along with Swoopes and Thompson. "New York is taking their hits
now, but when they get it together, they'll push through to win."

Rookie Sherill Baker scored 12 points for New York (2-8), which
has lost four of its last five. Becky Hammon and Shameka Christon
added 11 points apiece.

"Not a lot of good things happened out there tonight," Hammon
said. "We broke down offensively and defensively. We continue to
talk about the snowball effect, and it started to snow."

Houston took control at the end of the second quarter, closing
the first half with an 8-0 run to take a 37-31 lead. Swoopes, who
missed her first three shots, topped the 4,000-point mark with a
driving layup as time expired.

The Comets scored the first 11 points of the fourth quarter to
take a 65-45 lead with 7:09 left in the game. Thompson hit two
3-pointers during that stretch and made a free throw on a technical
called on Coyle.

"They're a good basketball team." Liberty coach Pat Coyle
said. "You have three Olympians, three All-Decade. They're a
pretty good team and you can't come out against a team like that
flat, and we came out flat."

Thompson was 3-for-3 on 3s in the second half after missing all
three attempts before the break.

"Initially they were squeezing me a lot and just hugging and
not giving me space," Thompson said. "I was being patient and
taking a lot more shots from the inside, and when the opportunity
opened up I took it."

Cathrine Kraayeveld's 3 with about 3 minutes left, and Hammon's
two free throws nearly 40 seconds later pulled New York to 70-56,
but the Liberty didn't get any closer.

"We played a good first half," Kraayeveld said. "We were able
to knock some shots down and played well on defense. We made some
mistakes in the second half that continued to pile on and we were
not able to recover from those mistakes."

Thompson opened the third quarter with a 3 and Swoopes had a
driving layup to stretch Houston's lead to 42-31 with 8:48 left.

Baker made two free throws with 2:26 left in the third to pull
the Liberty to 50-42. After Snow hit consecutive jumpers to push
Houston's lead to 12 with 43 seconds left, Christon hit a 3 13
seconds later.

The Comets improved to 8-1 when leading at halftime and 8-0 when
holding opponents under 70 points.
